{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"alias":"jaunty-pompous-lynx","description":"## Reproduction Steps\n\n1. Configure local signing (`[identity] signing_key` set; git email resolves to an identity — e.g. 594c).\n2. `rebar create task \"t\"` -> the CREATE event is SIGNED (`author_sig` present).\n3. `rebar transition <t> open idea` (or any claim/transition/close) -> the STATUS event is written with `author_id` stamped but **NO `author_sig`** (UNSIGNED).\n4. `rebar verify-identity --all --format json` lists that STATUS event as `unsigned` (in-scope, enforceable).\n\n**Expected:** transition/claim/close STATUS (and claim EDIT) events sign like CREATE/COMMENT do.\n**Actual:** they are attributed but unsigned.\n\n## Root cause\n\nCREATE/COMMENT are written via `src/rebar/_commands/_seam.append_event`, which calls\n`_apply_authorship` (the signing seam + write-gate). But transitions/claims/closes are written\nvia `src/rebar/_commands/txn.py` (`transition_core` ~L249-268, `claim_core` ~L341-372): these\nbuild the STATUS/EDIT event dicts, merge `attribution` (author_email/author_id) but write them\ndirectly via `fsutil.atomic_write` + git commit, **never calling `_apply_authorship`**. So the\ntransactional path signs nothing AND bypasses the require_authenticated write-gate.\n\n## Why this blocks the flip (dc09 / pristine-horrible-whapuku)\n\nThe CI merge-gate `.github/workflows/verify-identity.yaml` runs `rebar verify-identity` over the\nwhole tickets store with posture/boundary from `rebar.toml`. After `require_authenticated=true`\nlands, every NEW status transition (post-enforce_since) writes an unsigned in-scope STATUS event\nthat the gate flags -> the gate FAILS -> blocks landing. So enforcement is unsafe across the\ntxn writer until this is fixed. This is a foundational signing gap the epic's 5 stories did not\nanticipate (they assumed signing worked for all writers).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `transition_core` and `claim_core` in `src/rebar/_commands/txn.py` sign their STATUS (and\n      claim EDIT) events via the same signing seam CREATE/COMMENT use (`_apply_authorship` or an\n      equivalent), so a transition/claim/close under a configured signing key produces\n      `author_sig`.\n- [ ] Under `identity.require_authenticated`, an unsignable transition of a non-exempt ticket is\n      refused by the write-gate (parity with `append_event`), while gate-exempt types\n      (session_log/code_review/identity) are unaffected.\n- [ ] A held-out regression test asserts: with a signing key configured, a transition/claim\n      STATUS event has `author_sig` and `rebar verify-identity` reports it `verified`; without a\n      key + enforcement on, the transition is refused. Proving command: `make test`.\n- [ ] No regression to txn atomicity/locking (claim writes STATUS+EDIT in one commit).","id":"0ba4-6a28-7a88-47b2","parent_id":"","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"bug","title":"txn.py transitions/claims/closes write UNSIGNED in-scope STATUS/EDIT events (bypass the signing seam) — blocks safe require_authenticated flip"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1784244231026683001,"uuid":"e1042df1-02ee-413d-88ce-fe4fc5015b30"}